Meet Kevin Nguyen, Death & Co Los Angeles' new Head Bartender.⁠
⁠
Kevin (@kevindoesprep) has been an integral member of the Gin & Luck team since 2016, first joining us at The Normandie Club and The Walker Inn organizing prep operations and eventually becoming a barback, then bartender. Kevin was part of the opening bartending staff at Death & Co Los Angeles in 2019, and we're incredibly lucky to have him as our new Head Bartender. You'll often find Kevin using umeshu in his cocktails, trying new restaurants on his days off, and avoiding both ketchup and yellow mustard at any cost. Congratulations, Kevin! (📷: @meetjakob)

Introducing the Morris, a Death & Co x @helmboots collaboration.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
The Morris, named for Gin & Luck CEO David Kaplan’s (@dkproprietors) grandfather, is just one of numerous ways Morris Kaplan’s legacy endures. A phenomenal entrepreneur with a deep commitment to education, art, family, and philanthropy, Morris was also the inspiration for David to pursue his passion and build Death & Co. He’d often ask David about the bar, “How is your saloon?” and upon his first visit to Death & Co, triumphantly declared, “This is no saloon — this is some enterprise!” ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
All @helmboots are masterfully constructed with thought, care, and craft — not at all unlike our approach to making drinks. A perfect cross between a Chelsea boot and a sneaker, the Morris is a modern interpretation of a boot that can go with you anywhere. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
We're honored to partner with Helm on another addition to the Death & Co x Helm family. To take your pair home, head to the link in our bio.⁠⁠
(📷: @shawnxcampbell)

node.text: Mint is a wonderfully versatile herb for cocktails. It can be incorporated via muddling or steeping, or it can aromatize the top of a drink when it’s used as a garnish. That said, if you're building a drink like a classic Julep, we highly recommend playing with the template by substituting other herbs, whether other mint varieties (such as pineapple mint or chocolate mint) or basil in its many varieties, sage, and even thyme. Keep in mind that some herbs, like certain varieties of sage, can taste off-putting when muddled, and that muddling thyme creates a big mess and doesn’t taste that great. When substituting such herbs, you may want to use them simply as an aromatic garnish, or you might try extracting their flavor through an infusion or syrup instead. (📷: @dylanandjeni)

node.text:
@bittersandbrew took a page from Cocktail Codex and built a beautiful Pisco Sour featuring both lemon and lime juice. The pungency of the lime juice plays well with the gritty texture of the pisco, and the relative neutrality of lemon juice prevents the lime from taking over. Try it at home with our recipe below.⁠
⁠
2 oz. Pisco⁠
0.5 oz. Lemon juice⁠
0.5 oz. Lime juice⁠
0.75 oz. Simple syrup⁠
Egg white⁠
Add all ingredients to shaker and dry shake. Add ice and shake again. Double strain into a chilled cocktail glass and garnish with a few small drops of Angostura bitters. (📷: @bittersandbrew)

node.text: We don't often take shortcuts. Opportunities for streamlining a process? Yes. Instances that stand to improve from efficiency? Certainly. But shortcuts? Not exactly. That said, one of our current favorite dishes at DC/AM is the Buttermilk Pancake featuring breakfast sausage, maple syrup, and peanut butter. A satisfying disc of house-made sausage in the middle of a fluffy, light pancake is not a shortcut, in our minds, but a near-perfect means to a very delicious end. Consider this an invitation to join us at @theramblehotel for breakfast this weekend. (📷: @shawnxcampbell)

node.text: Our door policy — first come, first served — has remained the same at D&C East Village since our opening on New Year's Eve 2006 until last year, when our bars closed their doors for what we hoped, at the time, would only be a few days or weeks. Once we were able to begin the reopening process, we instated reservations for the first time in our history; now, almost a year later, we've returned to full operations and are enjoying every moment in our dark, welcoming space. Additionally, we've returned to our original door policy — we encourage you to stop by and if there's a wait, we'll take your name and number and let you know as soon as there's an opening at the bar. Thank you for your continued support and understanding; we couldn't do any of this without you. See you soon! (📷: @ericmedsker)

node.text: @matthewsbelanger's Melonball at Death & Co LA features an oft-overlooked fruit as a key ingredient: cantaloupe. Clarified cantaloupe juice is force carbonated to create a slightly sweet, flavorful addition to the cocktail's base of Suntory Toki Japanese Whisky and Hidalgo Oloroso Sherry. The resulting cocktail is light, bright, and, in our opinion, restores the reputation of the well-deserving cantaloupe. Try it on your next visit to D&C LA. (📷: @meetjakob)

node.text: There's a rhythm behind the bar that comes with busy evenings. Every movement is intentional, every step thoughtfully calculated. However, there's also a kind of magic within that rhythm that alights on certain nights — where everything feels easy, effortless, right. Not every evening is one of those, but the nights where the stars align just so make every challenge worth it. (📷: @shawnxcampbell)

node.text: Today is National Daiquiri Day, and while we're never in need of a particular reason to enjoy a daiquiri, we're using today as an excuse to try one of our favorite projects — experimenting with the cocktail's balance. A daiquiri’s balance is found through the collaboration between citrus and sugar and there is some flexibility in the amount of each depending on your preferences for tart or sweet. For our Goldilocks experiment to test where your preferences for sweet and sour fall, you'll need a shaker, jigger, cocktail strainer, three chilled coupes, ice, 2.5 oz of fresh lime juice, 2 oz of simple syrup, and, of course, a bottle of rum. For the purposes of this experiment, we forgo the garnish in order to keep the focus on the sweet-tart balance in the cocktail itself. Head to our Instagram stories for the step-by-step and let us know where you net out in the end. Cheers! (📷: @dylanandjeni)
